00:01:04.555 --> 00:01:09.060
Maxis's action RPG Darkspore was
removed from Steam because of, yes,

00:01:09.060 --> 00:01:12.120
you guessed it, server issues that
rendered the game unplayable.

00:01:12.120 --> 00:01:15.150
The game had been experiencing
these issues for months, and

00:01:15.150 --> 00:01:16.270
since its release in 2011,

00:01:16.270 --> 00:01:19.440
it's been plagued with server errors
that locked out players from the game.

00:01:19.440 --> 00:01:23.520
Before being shut down on Steam, Darkspore
was experiencing server-side issues that

00:01:23.520 --> 00:01:25.760
didn't even allow players
to save their characters.

00:01:25.760 --> 00:01:27.840
Since then,
an announcement on the official forum,

00:01:27.840 --> 00:01:30.980
started that Darkspore wouldn't be fixed,
and that the game was for

00:01:30.980 --> 00:01:33.892
almost all intents and
purposes an abandoned title.

00:01:33.892 --> 00:01:37.670
While Darkspore and its ongoing issues
aren't a very big deal in 2013,

00:01:37.670 --> 00:01:40.140
it sets an alarming
precedent with EA outright

00:01:40.140 --> 00:01:42.500
abandoning the game with
next to no explanation.

00:01:42.500 --> 00:01:45.320
So what does this mean for
future EA published games?

00:01:45.320 --> 00:01:47.790
When EA no longer sees value
in your favorite game,

00:01:47.790 --> 00:01:49.770
they may just pull
the plug without warning.

00:01:49.770 --> 00:01:50.770
