00:01:50.770 --> 00:01:54.460
this is exactly what Microsoft was
trying to prevent with the Xbox One,

00:01:54.460 --> 00:01:58.300
leaving game authentication to Microsoft
instead of individual publishers.

00:01:58.300 --> 00:02:01.720
Google has released some very interesting
statistics in a document called

00:02:01.720 --> 00:02:02.880
Gamers on YouTube.

00:02:02.880 --> 00:02:06.100
You guys should all check it out, but
the basic thesis is that time spent

00:02:06.100 --> 00:02:09.110
viewing game-related videos
has doubled year over year.

00:02:09.110 --> 00:02:11.840
About half of all views on
YouTube are from publishers

00:02:11.840 --> 00:02:13.540
before the launch of a video game.

00:02:13.540 --> 00:02:16.080
So this would be announcement videos,
gameplay demos,

00:02:16.080 --> 00:02:17.610
launch promotions, et cetera.

00:02:17.610 --> 00:02:20.290
And then once a game is released,
the community takes over and

00:02:20.290 --> 00:02:23.480
produces the other half of all
views over a game's lifespan.

00:02:23.480 --> 00:02:27.480
So this would be parody videos, funny
in-game footage, tutorials, walkthroughs,

00:02:27.480 --> 00:02:28.220
and last-plays.

00:02:28.220 --> 00:02:30.970
Especially interesting is
that before a game comes out,

00:02:30.970 --> 00:02:33.480
most views are coming
from desktop systems.

00:02:33.480 --> 00:02:36.590
But once a title is released,
those views transition to mobile.

00:02:36.590 --> 00:02:39.550
Presumably because gamers are playing
the game on their TV, and

00:02:39.550 --> 00:02:42.550
looking up videos about the game
on their phones while playing.

